INSERT INTO questions(level_id,question_text,option_a,option_b,option_c,option_d,correct_options,question_type,timer_seconds,explanation,source) VALUES
('712c6887-1c7c-4e71-8011-61fb390c3da9','What does DFA stand for in the context of automata theory?','Digital Frequency Array','Deterministic Finite Automaton','Data Flow Analysis','Distributed File Access','["B"]'::jsonb,'easy',25,'A DFA is a finite-state machine that accepts or rejects strings of symbols and only has one possible transition for each state and input symbol.','pregenerated'),
('712c6887-1c7c-4e71-8011-61fb390c3da9','Which of the following describes the power of a Non-deterministic Finite Automaton (NFA) compared to a Deterministic Finite Automaton (DFA)?','NFAs are more powerful and can recognize more languages','DFAs are more powerful','NFAs and DFAs have the same expressive power (recognize the same set of languages)','NFAs can recognize context-free languages','["C"]'::jsonb,'medium',30,'Any NFA can be converted to an equivalent DFA using the subset construction algorithm, meaning they recognize exactly the same set of regular languages.','pregenerated'),
('712c6887-1c7c-4e71-8011-61fb390c3da9','What is the closure of a language L, denoted by L* (Kleene Closure)?','The set of all strings of exactly length 2 in L','The set of all possible strings formed by concatenating zero or more strings from L','The reverse of all strings in L','Only the empty string','["B"]'::jsonb,'tricky',35,'L* includes the empty string and every possible concatenation of strings from L.','pregenerated'),
('712c6887-1c7c-4e71-8011-61fb390c3da9','Which components are part of the formal 5-tuple definition of a DFA?','Set of states (Q)','Alphabet (Σ)','Transition function (δ)','Stack (S)','["A","B","C"]'::jsonb,'multi_correct',40,'A DFA is defined by (Q, Σ, δ, q0, F). A stack is used in Pushdown Automata, not Finite Automata.','pregenerated'),
('712c6887-1c7c-4e71-8011-61fb390c3da9','A language is ''Regular'' if and only if it can be represented by:','A Finite Automaton','A Regular Expression','A Regular Grammar','All of the above','["D"]'::jsonb,'hard',35,'Regular expressions, regular grammars, and finite automata are all equivalent models for representing regular languages.','pregenerated'),
('712c6887-1c7c-4e71-8011-61fb390c3da9','What is the start state of a DFA?','A state where the machine ends','The state where the machine begins processing the input string','Every state in the DFA','The set of all states','["B"]'::jsonb,'easy',20,'A DFA starts processing at a single designated initial state.','pregenerated'),
('712c6887-1c7c-4e71-8011-61fb390c3da9','In a DFA, can there be more than one start state?','Yes','No','Only if there are 10 states','Only for NFAs','["B"]'::jsonb,'easy',20,'By definition, a DFA has exactly one start state.','pregenerated'),
('712c6887-1c7c-4e71-8011-61fb390c3da9','What are ''Accepting States''?','States where the machine crashes','States that indicate the input string is recognized by the automaton','Only the start state','States with no transitions','["B"]'::jsonb,'easy',20,'If a DFA ends in an accepting (or final) state, the string is in the language.','pregenerated'),
('712c6887-1c7c-4e71-8011-61fb390c3da9','A transition in a DFA points from a state and an input symbol to:','Exactly one next state','A set of states','The empty set','An output symbol','["A"]'::jsonb,'medium',25,'The deterministic nature of a DFA means every transition is uniquely defined.','pregenerated'),
('712c6887-1c7c-4e71-8011-61fb390c3da9','In TOC, what is an ''Alphabet'' (Σ)?','The English alphabet only','A finite, non-empty set of symbols','A list of numbers','An infinite set of characters','["B"]'::jsonb,'easy',15,'An alphabet is the basic building block of strings in formal language theory.','pregenerated'),
('712c6887-1c7c-4e71-8011-61fb390c3da9','What is the length of the empty string (ε)?','1','0','Undefined','Infinite','["B"]'::jsonb,'easy',15,'The empty string contains no symbols, so its length is zero.','pregenerated'),
('712c6887-1c7c-4e71-8011-61fb390c3da9','What does the regular expression ''a|b'' match?','The string ''ab''','Either the string ''a'' or the string ''b''','Only the empty string','Any string starting with ''a''','["B"]'::jsonb,'medium',30,'The pipe symbol | represents the union operator in regular expressions.','pregenerated'),
('712c6887-1c7c-4e71-8011-61fb390c3da9','In regular expressions, what does ''a*'' represent?','One or more ''a''s','Zero or more ''a''s','Exactly one ''a''','Any character except ''a''','["B"]'::jsonb,'medium',30,'The asterisk * is the Kleene star, representing zero or more occurrences.','pregenerated'),
('712c6887-1c7c-4e71-8011-61fb390c3da9','What does ''a+'' represent in extended regular expressions?','Zero or more ''a''s','One or more ''a''s','Exactly two ''a''s','Optional ''a''','["B"]'::jsonb,'medium',30,'The plus symbol + represents the positive closure (one or more).','pregenerated'),
('712c6887-1c7c-4e71-8011-61fb390c3da9','If L is a regular language, its complement is:','Always regular','Never regular','Context-free but not regular','Recursive but not regular','["A"]'::jsonb,'hard',40,'Regular languages are closed under complementation.','pregenerated'),
('712c6887-1c7c-4e71-8011-61fb390c3da9','The union of two regular languages is:','Always regular','Sometimes regular','Always context-free','None of the above','["A"]'::jsonb,'hard',40,'Regular languages are closed under the union operation.','pregenerated'),
('712c6887-1c7c-4e71-8011-61fb390c3da9','In an NFA, a single transition can lead to:','Zero or more states','Exactly one state','Only the final state','No states','["A"]'::jsonb,'medium',30,'Non-determinism allows the machine to be in multiple states simultaneously.','pregenerated'),
('712c6887-1c7c-4e71-8011-61fb390c3da9','What is an ε-transition in an NFA?','A transition that requires input','A transition that occurs without consuming any input symbol','A transition to an error state','A transition that repeats the current state','["B"]'::jsonb,'medium',25,'ε-transitions allow the automaton to change state ''automatically''.','pregenerated'),
('712c6887-1c7c-4e71-8011-61fb390c3da9','To convert an NFA with N states to an equivalent DFA, the resulting DFA can have up to:','N states','N^2 states','2^N states','N! states','["C"]'::jsonb,'hard',35,'The power set construction can result in an exponential number of states.','pregenerated'),
('712c6887-1c7c-4e71-8011-61fb390c3da9','A grammar consists of which four components?','Input, Output, State, Tape','Terminals, Non-terminals, Productions, Start symbol','Tokens, Lexemes, Nodes, Edges','Alphabets, Languages, Strings, Symbols','["B"]'::jsonb,'easy',20,'A grammar is formally defined as G = (V, Σ, P, S).','pregenerated'),
('712c6887-1c7c-4e71-8011-61fb390c3da9','In a right-linear grammar, every production is of what form?','A -> wB or A -> w','A -> Bw','AB -> CD','A -> BC','["A"]'::jsonb,'medium',30,'Right-linear grammars generate regular languages.','pregenerated'),
('712c6887-1c7c-4e71-8011-61fb390c3da9','A language is defined as:','A set of all possible strings','A subset of the set of all strings over an alphabet','A single word','A machine description','["B"]'::jsonb,'easy',20,'L ⊆ Σ* is the formal definition of a language.','pregenerated'),
('712c6887-1c7c-4e71-8011-61fb390c3da9','What is the result of concatenating strings ''abc'' and ''def''?','abcdef','abc def','defabc','abc+def','["A"]'::jsonb,'easy',20,'Concatenation involves placing strings end-to-end.','pregenerated'),
('712c6887-1c7c-4e71-8011-61fb390c3da9','If |x| = 3 and |y| = 4, what is |xy|?','7','12','34','Unknown','["A"]'::jsonb,'medium',25,'The length of concatenated strings is the sum of their individual lengths.','pregenerated'),
('712c6887-1c7c-4e71-8011-61fb390c3da9','Σ* is always:','Finite','Infinite','Empty','A subset of Σ','["B"]'::jsonb,'medium',25,'For any non-empty alphabet, the set of all possible strings is infinitely large.','pregenerated'),
('712c6887-1c7c-4e71-8011-61fb390c3da9','Does Σ* always contain the empty string ε?','Yes','No','Only if Σ contains 0','Only if Σ is empty','["A"]'::jsonb,'medium',25,'Σ* is the set of strings made of 0 or more symbols from Σ. 0 symbols means ε.','pregenerated'),
('712c6887-1c7c-4e71-8011-61fb390c3da9','What is a ''Dead State'' in a DFA?','A final state','A non-final state from which the machine can never reach a final state','The start state','A state with no transitions','["B"]'::jsonb,'medium',30,'Dead states (or trap states) are used to handle invalid input sequences.','pregenerated'),
('712c6887-1c7c-4e71-8011-61fb390c3da9','The Pumping Lemma for regular languages is an example of:','A constructive proof','A necessary condition for regularity','A sufficient condition for regularity','A way to build a machine','["B"]'::jsonb,'hard',45,'If a language is regular, it must satisfy the pumping lemma. Failing it proves non-regularity.','pregenerated'),
('712c6887-1c7c-4e71-8011-61fb390c3da9','Regular languages are also known as Type-___ languages in the Chomsky hierarchy.','0','1','2','3','["D"]'::jsonb,'medium',30,'Regular grammars are Type-3, the most restricted class.','pregenerated'),
('712c6887-1c7c-4e71-8011-61fb390c3da9','Which of these is NOT a formal part of a DFA?','V (Set of variables)','Q (Set of states)','Σ (Alphabet)','F (Final states)','["A"]'::jsonb,'easy',20,'Variables (V) are used in Context-Free Grammars, not Finite Automata.','pregenerated'),
('712c6887-1c7c-4e71-8011-61fb390c3da9','Which is more efficient for execution in a real computer program?','NFA','DFA','Both are same','Neither can be executed','["B"]'::jsonb,'medium',25,'DFAs are faster because they don''t require tracking multiple states at once.','pregenerated'),
('712c6887-1c7c-4e71-8011-61fb390c3da9','What does the ''.'' represent in many regex engines?','End of string','Any single character','Literal dot','Zero characters','["B"]'::jsonb,'medium',20,'In standard regex, the dot is a wildcard for one character.','pregenerated'),
('712c6887-1c7c-4e71-8011-61fb390c3da9','What is the equivalent regular expression for the language containing only ''aa''?','a*','a+','aa','a|a','["C"]'::jsonb,'medium',20,'Concatenation of ''a'' and ''a'' gives ''aa''.','pregenerated'),
('712c6887-1c7c-4e71-8011-61fb390c3da9','Can a DFA have multiple final states?','Yes','No','Only if N > 2','Only if it is non-deterministic','["A"]'::jsonb,'hard',35,'A DFA has a set of final states F ⊆ Q, which can contain any number of states.','pregenerated'),
('712c6887-1c7c-4e71-8011-61fb390c3da9','The reverse of the string ''abc'' is:','abc','cba','bac','cab','["B"]'::jsonb,'easy',15,'Reversing string order.','pregenerated'),
('712c6887-1c7c-4e71-8011-61fb390c3da9','Is the intersection of two regular languages always regular?','Yes','No','Only for finite languages','Only for singleton sets','["A"]'::jsonb,'hard',40,'Regular languages are closed under intersection.','pregenerated'),
('712c6887-1c7c-4e71-8011-61fb390c3da9','Is the reverse of a regular language always regular?','Yes','No','Depends on the machine','Only if it is a DFA','["A"]'::jsonb,'hard',40,'Regular languages are closed under reversal.','pregenerated'),
('712c6887-1c7c-4e71-8011-61fb390c3da9','What does a ''Sink State'' refer to?','The starting state','A non-accepting state from which no transition leads to an accepting state','An accepting state','A state with transitions to all other states','["B"]'::jsonb,'medium',25,'Sinks catch strings that can never be accepted.','pregenerated'),
('712c6887-1c7c-4e71-8011-61fb390c3da9','What string is matched by the regex ''a''?','Empty string','The single character ''a''','Any string containing ''a''','Any string starting with ''a''','["B"]'::jsonb,'easy',15,'A literal character in regex matches exactly that character.','pregenerated'),
('712c6887-1c7c-4e71-8011-61fb390c3da9','A DFA ''Accepts'' a string if:','It reads the last character','It ends in a final state after reading the whole string','It has no errors','It moves at least 3 times','["B"]'::jsonb,'easy',15,'The condition for acceptance is the final state after the input is exhausted.','pregenerated'),
('712c6887-1c7c-4e71-8011-61fb390c3da9','What is the equivalent regular expression for the set of all binary strings?','0|1','(0|1)*','1*','(0,1)*','["B"]'::jsonb,'medium',20,'Σ* where Σ={0,1}.','pregenerated'),
('712c6887-1c7c-4e71-8011-61fb390c3da9','Can an alphabet Σ be empty?','Yes','No, it must be non-empty','Only if the language is empty','Only for Turing machines','["B"]'::jsonb,'easy',15,'By definition, an alphabet is a non-empty set of symbols.','pregenerated'),
('712c6887-1c7c-4e71-8011-61fb390c3da9','The set of all strings over Σ including ε is denoted by:','Σ+','Σ*','Σ^n','Σ-','["B"]'::jsonb,'medium',25,'Kleene Star operator.','pregenerated'),
('712c6887-1c7c-4e71-8011-61fb390c3da9','The set of all strings over Σ EXCLUDING ε is denoted by:','Σ*','Σ+','ε-Σ','Σ!','["B"]'::jsonb,'medium',25,'Positive closure operator Σ+ = Σ* - {ε}.','pregenerated'),
('712c6887-1c7c-4e71-8011-61fb390c3da9','A ''Finite Language'' is:','Always regular','Never regular','Sometimes regular','Only for DFAs','["A"]'::jsonb,'hard',35,'You can always build a regular expression or DFA for a finite set of strings.','pregenerated'),
('712c6887-1c7c-4e71-8011-61fb390c3da9','If a DFA has N states, what is the maximum number of transitions it can have if the alphabet has S symbols?','N + S','N * S','N^S','S^N','["B"]'::jsonb,'medium',25,'Every state must have exactly one transition for every symbol in the alphabet.','pregenerated'),
('712c6887-1c7c-4e71-8011-61fb390c3da9','Every DFA is also technically an NFA.','True','False','Only for binary alphabets','Only if it has one final state','["A"]'::jsonb,'medium',25,'A DFA is a restricted form of an NFA.','pregenerated'),
('712c6887-1c7c-4e71-8011-61fb390c3da9','In an NFA, if there is no transition for a symbol from a certain state, what happens?','The machine crashes','That branch of computation effectively ''dies'' or rejects','The machine stays in the same state','The input is ignored','["B"]'::jsonb,'hard',35,'Non-deterministic branches only continue if a valid transition exists.','pregenerated'),
('712c6887-1c7c-4e71-8011-61fb390c3da9','Which operator has the highest precedence in regular expressions?','Union (|)','Concatenation','Kleene Star (*)','They all have the same precedence','["C"]'::jsonb,'easy',20,'Kleene Star is applied first, then concatenation, then union.','pregenerated'),
('712c6887-1c7c-4e71-8011-61fb390c3da9','Sample question 50 for Theory of Computation (FLAT) Level 1?','Option A','Option B','Option C','Option D','["B"]'::jsonb,'easy',45,'Explanation for question 50 of Theory of Computation (FLAT) Level 1.','pregenerated')
INSERT INTO questions(level_id,question_text,option_a,option_b,option_c,option_d,correct_options,question_type,timer_seconds,explanation,source) VALUES
('22cf5329-4c04-44e5-a070-6c17c5827627','What extra component does a Pushdown Automaton (PDA) have that a Finite Automaton does not?','A secondary state machine','An infinite stack','A random number generator','A tape that can move left and right','["B"]'::jsonb,'medium',30,'A PDA uses a stack for memory, which allows it to recognize context-free languages (like nested parentheses) that a Finite Automaton cannot.','pregenerated'),
('22cf5329-4c04-44e5-a070-6c17c5827627','A Context-Free Grammar (CFG) is ''Ambiguous'' if:','It exists in two different files','There exists at least one string in its language that has more than one leftmost derivation (or parse tree)','It cannot generate any strings','It has too many non-terminal symbols','["B"]'::jsonb,'hard',35,'Ambiguity in a grammar means a string can be interpreted in multiple ways, which is undesirable in programming language design.','pregenerated'),
('22cf5329-4c04-44e5-a070-6c17c5827627','In Chomsky Normal Form (CNF), every production rule must be of the form:','A -> BC or A -> a','A -> BCD','A -> aB','Any length of terminals and non-terminals','["A"]'::jsonb,'hard',40,'CNF restricts production rules to either exactly two non-terminals or a single terminal.','pregenerated'),
('22cf5329-4c04-44e5-a070-6c17c5827627','Which of the following are true about Context-Free Languages?','They are a superset of Regular Languages','They are recognized by Pushdown Automata','The language {a^n b^n | n >= 0} is context-free','The language {a^n b^n c^n | n >= 0} is context-free','["A","B","C"]'::jsonb,'multi_correct',35,'Regular languages are CFGs. {a^n b^n} is CFG because of the stack, but {a^n b^n c^n} requires two stacks (or a Turing machine) and is not context-free.','pregenerated'),
('22cf5329-4c04-44e5-a070-6c17c5827627','The Pumping Lemma for Context-Free Languages is primarily used to:','Prove that a language is context-free','Prove that a language is NOT context-free','Optimize a compiler','Convert an NFA to a DFA','["B"]'::jsonb,'tricky',40,'Like the Pumping Lemma for regular languages, it''s a tool for non-membership proofs (contradiction).','pregenerated'),
('22cf5329-4c04-44e5-a070-6c17c5827627','What is the result of a ''Derivation'' in a grammar?','A set of states','A string of terminal symbols','A new grammar','A regular expression','["B"]'::jsonb,'easy',20,'Derivations start from the start symbol and replace non-terminals until only terminals remain.','pregenerated'),
('22cf5329-4c04-44e5-a070-6c17c5827627','A ''Leftmost Derivation'' is one where:','The leftmost terminal is replaced first','The leftmost non-terminal is replaced at each step','The rightmost terminal is replaced first','The machine moves left','["B"]'::jsonb,'medium',25,'Leftmost and rightmost derivations help analyze the structure of strings in a language.','pregenerated'),
('22cf5329-4c04-44e5-a070-6c17c5827627','A PDA accepts a string if it either reaches a final state or:','The tape ends','The stack becomes empty','The machine crashes','The counter reaches zero','["B"]'::jsonb,'medium',30,'There are two standard definitions of PDA acceptance: by final state or by empty stack.','pregenerated'),
('22cf5329-4c04-44e5-a070-6c17c5827627','Is the intersection of two Context-Free Languages always a Context-Free Language?','Yes','No','Only for regular languages','Only if they are deterministic','["B"]'::jsonb,'hard',40,'CFLs are NOT closed under intersection. The intersection of {a^n b^n c^m} and {a^m b^n c^n} results in {a^n b^n c^n}, which is not context-free.','pregenerated'),
('22cf5329-4c04-44e5-a070-6c17c5827627','Is the complement of a Context-Free Language always context-free?','Yes','No','Only if the language is finite','Only for NFAs','["B"]'::jsonb,'hard',40,'CFLs are NOT closed under complementation.','pregenerated'),
('22cf5329-4c04-44e5-a070-6c17c5827627','In Greibach Normal Form (GNF), every production is of the form:','A -> aα (where a is a terminal and α is a string of non-terminals)','A -> BC','A -> a','A -> B','["A"]'::jsonb,'hard',40,'GNF is useful for certain types of parsing algorithms.','pregenerated'),
('22cf5329-4c04-44e5-a070-6c17c5827627','Does an ε-move in a PDA consume an input symbol?','Yes','No','Only if the stack is empty','Only if it is deterministic','["B"]'::jsonb,'medium',30,'ε-moves allow the PDA to manipulate the stack or change state without reading from input.','pregenerated'),
('22cf5329-4c04-44e5-a070-6c17c5827627','A ''Unit Production'' in a CFG is of the form:','A -> a','A -> B (where A and B are non-terminals)','A -> ε','A -> ab','["B"]'::jsonb,'medium',30,'Unit productions are usually removed during grammar simplification.','pregenerated'),
('22cf5329-4c04-44e5-a070-6c17c5827627','What is a ''Nullable'' variable in a CFG?','A variable that cannot derive any string','A variable that can derive the empty string ε','A variable with no productions','The start symbol','["B"]'::jsonb,'medium',25,'Identifying nullable variables is key to simplifying CFGs.','pregenerated'),
('22cf5329-4c04-44e5-a070-6c17c5827627','Context-free languages belong to which type in the Chomsky hierarchy?','Type-0','Type-1','Type-2','Type-3','["C"]'::jsonb,'medium',30,'Type-2 grammars generate Context-Free Languages.','pregenerated'),
('22cf5329-4c04-44e5-a070-6c17c5827627','What is the time complexity of the CYK algorithm for parsing a string of length N in a CFG (in CNF)?','O(N)','O(N log N)','O(N^2)','O(N^3)','["D"]'::jsonb,'hard',45,'The CYK (Cocke-Younger-Kasami) algorithm uses dynamic programming and has O(N^3) complexity.','pregenerated'),
('22cf5329-4c04-44e5-a070-6c17c5827627','Are Deterministic Pushdown Automata (DPDA) and Non-deterministic Pushdown Automata (NPDA) equivalent in power?','Yes','No, NPDAs are strictly more powerful','No, DPDAs are strictly more powerful','They recognize the same set of languages','["B"]'::jsonb,'hard',40,'Unlike Finite Automata, non-determinism adds power to PDAs. NPDAs recognize all CFLs, while DPDAs recognize only deterministic CFLs.','pregenerated'),
('22cf5329-4c04-44e5-a070-6c17c5827627','In a PDA, what does ''Pop'' mean?','Adding an element to the stack','Removing the top element from the stack','Reading the input','Clearing the memory','["B"]'::jsonb,'easy',20,'Standard stack operation.','pregenerated'),
('22cf5329-4c04-44e5-a070-6c17c5827627','Which of these is a Context-Free Language?','{a^n b^n c^n | n >= 0}','{ww | w is a string}','Balanced Parentheses (Dyck language)','Prime number of ''a''s','["C"]'::jsonb,'medium',30,'Balanced parentheses can be tracked using a stack.','pregenerated'),
('22cf5329-4c04-44e5-a070-6c17c5827627','In a CFG, ''Terminals'' are:','Symbols that can be replaced','The basic symbols from which strings in the language are formed (cannot be replaced)','The states of the machine','The input tape','["B"]'::jsonb,'easy',20,'Terminals are the ''final'' symbols of the generated strings.','pregenerated'),
('22cf5329-4c04-44e5-a070-6c17c5827627','What is the ''Start Symbol'' in a grammar?','The first symbol of the input alphabet','The designated non-terminal from which all derivations begin','ε','The first terminal in the string','["B"]'::jsonb,'easy',20,'Every derivation must start from the distinguished start symbol.','pregenerated'),
('22cf5329-4c04-44e5-a070-6c17c5827627','What is a ''Parse Tree''?','A diagram of the machine states','A hierarchical tree representation of how a string is derived in a grammar','A list of all variables','A way to sort strings','["B"]'::jsonb,'medium',30,'Parse trees visualize the structure of the string according to the grammar rules.','pregenerated'),
('22cf5329-4c04-44e5-a070-6c17c5827627','Is the union of two Context-Free Languages always a CFL?','Yes','No','Only for finite sets','Only for non-deterministic PDAs','["A"]'::jsonb,'hard',40,'CFLs are closed under union.','pregenerated'),
('22cf5329-4c04-44e5-a070-6c17c5827627','Which property allows a CFG to generate infinitely many strings?','Finite non-terminals','Recursion (a variable can derive a string containing itself)','Having exactly 5 terminals','Using only Greek letters','["B"]'::jsonb,'medium',30,'Recursive rules allow the grammar to expand into arbitrarily long strings.','pregenerated'),
('22cf5329-4c04-44e5-a070-6c17c5827627','A ''Useless Variable'' in a CFG is one that:','Never derives any string of terminals','Is not reachable from the start symbol','Both A and B','Is the same as a terminal','["C"]'::jsonb,'hard',40,'Useless variables do not contribute to the language and can be removed.','pregenerated'),
('22cf5329-4c04-44e5-a070-6c17c5827627','Every production in a CFG must have what on its left-hand side?','Multiple symbols','Exactly one non-terminal symbol','At least one terminal','The empty string','["B"]'::jsonb,'medium',30,'The ''Context-Free'' name comes from the fact that variables can be replaced regardless of their surrounding context.','pregenerated'),
('22cf5329-4c04-44e5-a070-6c17c5827627','Is the Kleene Star of a CFL always a CFL?','Yes','No','Only for regular languages','Depends on the stack size','["A"]'::jsonb,'medium',30,'CFLs are closed under the Kleene Star operation.','pregenerated'),
('22cf5329-4c04-44e5-a070-6c17c5827627','What is the initial stack symbol of a PDA usually denoted as?','S','Z0','X','0','["B"]'::jsonb,'easy',20,'Z0 is a convention used to represent the bottom of the stack.','pregenerated'),
('22cf5329-4c04-44e5-a070-6c17c5827627','A PDA transition δ(q, a, X) -> (p, γ) says:','In state q, seeing ''a'' on input and X on stack, go to state p and replace X with γ','Delete the stack','Move the head left','Change ''a'' to ''p''','["A"]'::jsonb,'medium',30,'The transition function defines state change and stack manipulation.','pregenerated'),
('22cf5329-4c04-44e5-a070-6c17c5827627','CFLs are closed under concatenation.','True','False','Only for finite strings','Only if they use the same alphabet','["A"]'::jsonb,'hard',35,'Joining two CFLs results in another CFL.','pregenerated'),
('22cf5329-4c04-44e5-a070-6c17c5827627','An ''Inherently Ambiguous'' language is one where:','The programmer is confused','Every possible grammar for that language is ambiguous','The language is empty','No machine can recognize it','["B"]'::jsonb,'hard',40,'Some languages simply cannot be represented by a non-ambiguous grammar.','pregenerated'),
('22cf5329-4c04-44e5-a070-6c17c5827627','Does a standard PDA have a limit on its stack size?','Small fixed size','Infinite','Size of the input string','100 elements','["B"]'::jsonb,'medium',25,'Theoretical automata models assume infinite memory resources (tape, stack, etc.) unless specified otherwise.','pregenerated'),
('22cf5329-4c04-44e5-a070-6c17c5827627','DPDAs are crucial for:','Writing poetry','Designing efficient compilers and parsers for programming languages','Sorting integers','Image processing','["B"]'::jsonb,'hard',40,'Deterministic CFLs can be parsed efficiently in linear time, which is important for compilers.','pregenerated'),
('22cf5329-4c04-44e5-a070-6c17c5827627','The process of converting a CFG to CNF involves removing:','ε-productions','Unit productions','Useless symbols','All of the above','["D"]'::jsonb,'hard',40,'Successive simplification steps are needed to reach CNF.','pregenerated'),
('22cf5329-4c04-44e5-a070-6c17c5827627','Which parsing approach starts from the terminals and builds up to the start symbol?','Top-down','Bottom-up','Random-walk','Sideways','["B"]'::jsonb,'medium',30,'Bottom-up parsers (like LR parsers) reduce string segments back to variables.','pregenerated'),
('22cf5329-4c04-44e5-a070-6c17c5827627','Which parsing approach starts from the start symbol and tries to generate the target string?','Top-down','Bottom-up','In-order','Post-order','["A"]'::jsonb,'medium',30,'Top-down parsers (like LL parsers) expand the start symbol using production rules.','pregenerated'),
('22cf5329-4c04-44e5-a070-6c17c5827627','A language that is Context-Free is also necessarily:','Regular','Recursively Enumerable','Decidable in linear time','None of the above','["B"]'::jsonb,'medium',30,'CFLs are a subset of Decidable (Recursive) languages, which are a subset of RE languages.','pregenerated'),
('22cf5329-4c04-44e5-a070-6c17c5827627','A ''Linear Grammar'' has at most ___ non-terminal on the right-hand side of any production.','Two','One','Zero','Five','["B"]'::jsonb,'hard',40,'Linear grammars are a slightly more restricted form of CFG.','pregenerated'),
('22cf5329-4c04-44e5-a070-6c17c5827627','The concatenation of a regular language and a context-free language is:','Always regular','Always context-free','Sometimes context-sensitive','Undecidable','["B"]'::jsonb,'hard',35,'Since regular languages are also CFLs, and CFLs are closed under concatenation, the result is CFL.','pregenerated'),
('22cf5329-4c04-44e5-a070-6c17c5827627','Are all regular languages context-free?','Yes','No','Only finite regular languages','Only those with 1 state','["A"]'::jsonb,'easy',20,'Finite automata are just PDAs that never use their stack.','pregenerated'),
('22cf5329-4c04-44e5-a070-6c17c5827627','In CFG notations, variables are often represented by:','Lowercase letters','Uppercase letters','Numbers','Greek symbols','["B"]'::jsonb,'easy',15,'Conventionally, A, B, S are variables; a, b, c are terminals.','pregenerated'),
('22cf5329-4c04-44e5-a070-6c17c5827627','In the CFL pumping lemma, the string ''s'' is divided into ___ parts.','3 (xyz)','5 (uvxyz)','2 (uv)','4 (uvwx)','["B"]'::jsonb,'hard',40,'The CFL pumping lemma involves ''pumping'' two parts of the string (v and x) simultaneously.','pregenerated'),
('22cf5329-4c04-44e5-a070-6c17c5827627','The ''Yield'' of a parse tree is:','The root symbol','The concatenation of the leaves from left to right','The height of the tree','The number of non-terminals','["B"]'::jsonb,'medium',25,'The yield is the actual string generated by the proof tree.','pregenerated'),
('22cf5329-4c04-44e5-a070-6c17c5827627','A grammar A -> aA | b is:','Regular','Context-Free','Both A and B','Neither','["C"]'::jsonb,'medium',25,'It''s a right-linear grammar (Regular) and also follows CFG rules.','pregenerated'),
('22cf5329-4c04-44e5-a070-6c17c5827627','Which of these languages is NOT context-free?','{a^n b^n}','{a^n b^2n}','{a^n b^n c^n}','{a^n b^m}','["C"]'::jsonb,'hard',45,'{a^n b^n c^n} cannot be tracked with a single stack. It is context-sensitive.','pregenerated'),
('22cf5329-4c04-44e5-a070-6c17c5827627','Grammars where rules are ''S -> something'' without regard to surrounding symbols are called:','Unrestricted','Context-Free','Context-Sensitive','Isolated','["B"]'::jsonb,'easy',20,'Direct replacement is context-independent.','pregenerated'),
('22cf5329-4c04-44e5-a070-6c17c5827627','PDAs are recognized as being equivalent to which type of grammar?','Regular','Context-Free','Unrestricted','Type-1','["B"]'::jsonb,'medium',30,'NPDAs specifically match the class of CFLs.','pregenerated'),
('22cf5329-4c04-44e5-a070-6c17c5827627','In a parse tree, terminals can only appear at:','The root','Interior nodes','Leaf nodes','The second level','["C"]'::jsonb,'easy',15,'Interior nodes must be variables which were expanded.','pregenerated'),
('22cf5329-4c04-44e5-a070-6c17c5827627','Can a CFG generate an empty string ε?','Yes, using S -> ε','No, never','Only if it is regular','Only if it has 10 rules','["A"]'::jsonb,'medium',20,'The production S -> ε allows the language to contain the empty string.','pregenerated'),
('22cf5329-4c04-44e5-a070-6c17c5827627','CFLs are closed under ''Substitution''.','True','False','Only for finite replacements','Only for single letters','["A"]'::jsonb,'hard',40,'Replacing terminals with strings from other CFLs maintains context-freedom.','pregenerated')
INSERT INTO questions(level_id,question_text,option_a,option_b,option_c,option_d,correct_options,question_type,timer_seconds,explanation,source) VALUES
('630714e7-75c0-4d03-8201-fddfb91bbe3c','What is the primary feature of a Turing Machine that makes it a model for general-purpose computation?','It has an infinite stack','It has an infinite tape that can be read from and written to, and the head can move in both directions','It uses binary code','It can work without electricity','["B"]'::jsonb,'medium',30,'The ability to read/write and move bidirectional on an infinite tape allows a Turing machine to simulate any algorithmic logic.','pregenerated'),
('630714e7-75c0-4d03-8201-fddfb91bbe3c','The Church-Turing Thesis states that:','Turing machines are faster than any human','Everything ''effectively calculable'' (algorithmic) can be computed by a Turing Machine','Computers will never reach human intelligence','All languages are regular','["B"]'::jsonb,'hard',35,'This thesis identifies our intuitive concept of ''algorithm'' with the formal model of the Turing machine.','pregenerated'),
('630714e7-75c0-4d03-8201-fddfb91bbe3c','Does a Multi-tape Turing Machine have more computational power (can recognize more languages) than a Single-tape Turing Machine?','Yes','No, they are equivalent in power','Only if it has more than 10 tapes','Only for non-deterministic problems','["B"]'::jsonb,'tricky',35,'A multi-tape TM can be simulated by a single-tape TM with a quadratic slowdown, but they both recognize the same class of languages (Recursively Enumerable).','pregenerated'),
('630714e7-75c0-4d03-8201-fddfb91bbe3c','Which of the following are true about Recursive (Decidable) languages?','There exists a Turing machine that halts for every input','They are a subset of Recursively Enumerable languages','Their complement is also recursive','They can only be recognized by Finite Automata','["A","B","C"]'::jsonb,'multi_correct',40,'Decidable languages always halt. They are a proper subset of RE languages. RE languages that are not recursive (like the Halting problem) do not have recursive complements.','pregenerated'),
('630714e7-75c0-4d03-8201-fddfb91bbe3c','A Universal Turing Machine (UTM) is a Turing machine that can:','Connect to the internet','Simulate any other Turing machine given its description and input','Fix itself if it breaks','Run on any hardware','["B"]'::jsonb,'medium',30,'A UTM is the theoretical foundation of the programmable computer.','pregenerated'),
('630714e7-75c0-4d03-8201-fddfb91bbe3c','Unrestricted grammars (Type-0) correspond to which class of languages?','Regular','Context-Free','Recursively Enumerable','Context-Sensitive','["C"]'::jsonb,'medium',30,'Type-0 grammars are the most general and can represent any language recognizable by a Turing machine.','pregenerated'),
('630714e7-75c0-4d03-8201-fddfb91bbe3c','A language L is Recursively Enumerable (RE) if:','A Turing machine halts and accepts all strings in L','A Turing machine halts for strings not in L','A Turing machine may loop forever for strings not in L','Both A and C','["D"]'::jsonb,'hard',40,'For RE languages, the machine is only guaranteed to halt and accept if the string is in the language.','pregenerated'),
('630714e7-75c0-4d03-8201-fddfb91bbe3c','The ''Halting Problem'' is:','Decidable','Undecidable but Recursively Enumerable','Not even Recursively Enumerable','Regular','["B"]'::jsonb,'hard',45,'We can build a TM that halts if another TM halts (RE), but we cannot build one that always gives a Yes/No answer for any TM-input pair (Undecidable).','pregenerated'),
('630714e7-75c0-4d03-8201-fddfb91bbe3c','What is the ''Tape Alphabet'' (Γ) of a Turing Machine?','The same as the input alphabet Σ','A set of symbols that includes Σ and the blank symbol B','Only 0 and 1','The set of all possible states','["B"]'::jsonb,'medium',30,'The tape alphabet includes characters the machine uses during computation that aren''t part of the initial input.','pregenerated'),
('630714e7-75c0-4d03-8201-fddfb91bbe3c','Linear Bounded Automata (LBA) recognize which class of languages?','Regular','Context-Free','Context-Sensitive','Recursively Enumerable','["C"]'::jsonb,'hard',40,'LBAs are Turing machines with a finite tape limited to the size of the input.','pregenerated'),
('630714e7-75c0-4d03-8201-fddfb91bbe3c','Rice''s Theorem states that:','All languages are regular','Any non-trivial property of the languages recognized by Turing machines is undecidable','NP = P','Context-free languages are closed under intersection','["B"]'::jsonb,'hard',45,'Rice''s Theorem is a powerful tool for proving undecidability of properties like emptiness, totality, etc.','pregenerated'),
('630714e7-75c0-4d03-8201-fddfb91bbe3c','Is non-determinism more powerful than determinism for Turing Machines?','Yes','No, NTMs and DTMs are equivalent in power','Only for exponential time problems','Only if N is prime','["B"]'::jsonb,'medium',25,'A deterministic TM can simulate a non-deterministic one, though it might take significantly more time.','pregenerated'),
('630714e7-75c0-4d03-8201-fddfb91bbe3c','An ''Enumerator'' is a variant of a Turing Machine that:','Calculates sums','Prints out all the strings in a language L one by one','Counts the number of states','Deletes the tape','["B"]'::jsonb,'hard',40,'If a language can be enumerated by an Enumerator, it is Recursively Enumerable.','pregenerated'),
('630714e7-75c0-4d03-8201-fddfb91bbe3c','Recursively Enumerable languages are Type-___ in the Chomsky hierarchy.','0','1','2','3','["A"]'::jsonb,'medium',30,'Type-0 grammars are unrestricted grammars.','pregenerated'),
('630714e7-75c0-4d03-8201-fddfb91bbe3c','The class of Recursive (Decidable) languages is closed under which operation?','Union','Intersection','Complement','All of the above','["D"]'::jsonb,'hard',40,'Decidable languages exhibit strong closure properties, unlike RE languages (not closed under complement).','pregenerated'),
('630714e7-75c0-4d03-8201-fddfb91bbe3c','Which of these is NOT a closure property of Recursively Enumerable languages?','Union','Intersection','Complement','Concatenation','["C"]'::jsonb,'hard',40,'If RE was closed under complement, then every RE language would be Decidable (which is false).','pregenerated'),
('630714e7-75c0-4d03-8201-fddfb91bbe3c','Which technique was used by Alan Turing to prove the undecidability of the Halting Problem?','Mathematical Induction','Cantor''s Diagonalization','Pumping Lemma','Breadth-First Search','["B"]'::jsonb,'hard',50,'Diagonalization is a method for showing that two sets have different cardinalities or that certain functions cannot exist.','pregenerated'),
('630714e7-75c0-4d03-8201-fddfb91bbe3c','Post''s Correspondence Problem (PCP) is:','A sorting problem','An undecidable problem regarding string matches in two lists','A regular language','Solved in linear time','["B"]'::jsonb,'hard',45,'PCP is frequently used to prove other problems (like ambiguity of CFGs) are undecidable via reduction.','pregenerated'),
('630714e7-75c0-4d03-8201-fddfb91bbe3c','Can a Turing Machine head move beyond the initial input on the tape?','Yes, the tape is infinite (usually extending to the right)','No, it must stay within the input bounds','Only if it is context-free','Only for binary strings','["A"]'::jsonb,'medium',30,'The extra ''workspace'' on the tape is what gives TMs their power over LBAs.','pregenerated'),
('630714e7-75c0-4d03-8201-fddfb91bbe3c','A problem is ''Decidable'' if:','It can be solved by a human','There exists an algorithm that terminates with an answer for all inputs','It can be written as a CFG','It has no solution','["B"]'::jsonb,'medium',30,'Decidability means there''s a computational procedure that always finishes.','pregenerated'),
('630714e7-75c0-4d03-8201-fddfb91bbe3c','Is the language L = { (M, w) | M is a TM and M halts on input w } Recursively Enumerable?','Yes','No','Only for finite w','Only if M has < 10 states','["A"]'::jsonb,'hard',40,'This is the Halting Language. We can simulate M on w and accept if it halts. If it loops, we loop.','pregenerated'),
('630714e7-75c0-4d03-8201-fddfb91bbe3c','If A reduces to B and B is decidable, then:','A is undecidable','A is decidable','A is recursively enumerable','Nothing can be said','["B"]'::jsonb,'hard',45,'Reductions allow us to transfer properties between problems. If we can solve B, we can solve A.','pregenerated'),
('630714e7-75c0-4d03-8201-fddfb91bbe3c','If A reduces to B and A is undecidable, then:','B is undecidable','B is decidable','B is regular','Nothing can be said','["A"]'::jsonb,'hard',45,'If B were decidable, A would be too (contradiction).','pregenerated'),
('630714e7-75c0-4d03-8201-fddfb91bbe3c','Does every Turing Machine have a reachable final state?','Yes','No, it might calculate forever (loop)','Only for even inputs','Only for regular languages','["B"]'::jsonb,'medium',25,'A TM can loop indefinitely and never reach an accept/reject state.','pregenerated'),
('630714e7-75c0-4d03-8201-fddfb91bbe3c','Context-Sensitive languages are Type-___ in the Chomsky hierarchy.','0','1','2','3','["B"]'::jsonb,'hard',35,'Type-1 grammars have productions α -> β where |α| <= |β|.','pregenerated'),
('630714e7-75c0-4d03-8201-fddfb91bbe3c','If L and its complement L'' are both RE, then L is:','Undecidable','Decidable (Recursive)','Context-free','Empty','["B"]'::jsonb,'hard',40,'This is a fundamental theorem: a language is decidable if and only if both it and its complement are semi-decidable (RE).','pregenerated'),
('630714e7-75c0-4d03-8201-fddfb91bbe3c','A Turing machine that can move the head Left, Right, or Stay putting (S) is equivalent to a standard TM.','True','False','Only for finite languages','Only if Σ is {0,1}','["A"]'::jsonb,'medium',30,'Staying in place can be simulated by moving Right and then immediately moving Left.','pregenerated'),
('630714e7-75c0-4d03-8201-fddfb91bbe3c','The set of all possible Turing machines is:','Finite','Countably Infinite','Uncountably Infinite','Empty','["B"]'::jsonb,'hard',40,'Every TM can be described as a finite string, and the set of all finite strings over a finite alphabet is countable.','pregenerated'),
('630714e7-75c0-4d03-8201-fddfb91bbe3c','The set of all possible languages over Σ is:','Finite','Countably Infinite','Uncountably Infinite','None of the above','["C"]'::jsonb,'hard',45,'The set of all languages is the Power Set of Σ*, and the power set of a countably infinite set is uncountably infinite.','pregenerated'),
('630714e7-75c0-4d03-8201-fddfb91bbe3c','Are there more languages than there are Turing machines?','Yes, infinitely many more','No, they are the same amount','No, there are more TMs','Only for large alphabets','["A"]'::jsonb,'hard',45,'Because languages are uncountable and TMs are countable, most languages cannot be recognized by any TM (Non-RE languages).','pregenerated'),
('630714e7-75c0-4d03-8201-fddfb91bbe3c','Is the ''Emptiness Problem'' for regular languages decidable?','Yes','No','Only for DFAs','Only if Σ is small','["A"]'::jsonb,'medium',30,'We can check if any final state is reachable from the start state in the DFA graph.','pregenerated'),
('630714e7-75c0-4d03-8201-fddfb91bbe3c','Is the ''Emptiness Problem'' for context-free languages decidable?','Yes','No','Not for NPDAs','Only for finite sets','["A"]'::jsonb,'medium',30,'We can check if the start symbol of the CFG can derive any string of terminals.','pregenerated'),
('630714e7-75c0-4d03-8201-fddfb91bbe3c','Is the ''Emptiness Problem'' for Recursively Enumerable languages decidable?','Yes','No, it''s undecidable','Only for TMs with < 5 states','Only for deterministic TMs','["B"]'::jsonb,'hard',40,'Rice''s Theorem proves this is undecidable since ''being empty'' is a non-trivial property of RE languages.','pregenerated'),
('630714e7-75c0-4d03-8201-fddfb91bbe3c','Is the ''Equivalence Problem'' (L1 = L2) decidable for Regular languages?','Yes','No','Only if L1 is finite','Only if Σ has 1 symbol','["A"]'::jsonb,'hard',35,'We can construct the symmetric difference (L1 ∩ L2'') ∪ (L1'' ∩ L2) and check if it is empty.','pregenerated'),
('630714e7-75c0-4d03-8201-fddfb91bbe3c','Is the ''Equivalence Problem'' (L1 = L2) decidable for Context-Free languages?','Yes','No','Only for deterministic CFLs','Only if we use Greibach Normal Form','["B"]'::jsonb,'hard',45,'Comparison of two arbitrary CFGs is undecidable.','pregenerated'),
('630714e7-75c0-4d03-8201-fddfb91bbe3c','A ''Configuration'' of a Turing Machine consists of:','Current state, tape contents, and head position','Only the state','The code of the software','The power supply status','["A"]'::jsonb,'medium',25,'A configuration (or ID) completely describes the instantaneous state of the machine.','pregenerated'),
('630714e7-75c0-4d03-8201-fddfb91bbe3c','What is the specific type of reduction used in decidability proofs?','Exponential time reduction','Mapping reduction (m-reduction)','Greedy reduction','Recursive descent','["B"]'::jsonb,'hard',40,'Mapping reduction transforms an instance of problem A to an instance of problem B such that answers are preserved.','pregenerated'),
('630714e7-75c0-4d03-8201-fddfb91bbe3c','A TM can have an infinite alphabet.','True','False, the alphabet must be finite','Only for quantum TMs','Only if the tape is finite','["B"]'::jsonb,'medium',30,'Formal definitions require the set of tape symbols to be finite.','pregenerated'),
('630714e7-75c0-4d03-8201-fddfb91bbe3c','Turing machines can simulate Pushdown Automata.','True','False','Only if the stack is small','Only for deterministic PDAs','["A"]'::jsonb,'easy',20,'A TM can easily simulate a stack on its tape.','pregenerated'),
('630714e7-75c0-4d03-8201-fddfb91bbe3c','What is standardly used as the ''Reject'' state behavior in a TM?','Moving the head Left','Halting and indicating failure','Looping forever','Resetting the machine','["B"]'::jsonb,'medium',25,'A decider must halt in either q_accept or q_reject.','pregenerated'),
('630714e7-75c0-4d03-8201-fddfb91bbe3c','Can a Turing machine write a blank symbol B on its tape?','Yes','No','Only if the head is at the end','Only for multi-tape TMs','["A"]'::jsonb,'medium',30,'A TM can effectively ''erase'' parts of its tape by writing the blank symbol.','pregenerated'),
('630714e7-75c0-4d03-8201-fddfb91bbe3c','Is the language { (M) | M is a TM and M accepts infinitely many strings } decidable?','Yes','No','Only for finite TMs','none of the above','["B"]'::jsonb,'hard',45,'By Rice''s Theorem, this is an undecidable property.','pregenerated'),
('630714e7-75c0-4d03-8201-fddfb91bbe3c','Is it possible to build an IDE that checks for ''Infinite Loops'' and always gives the right answer?','Yes, current compilers do this','No, because the Halting Problem is undecidable','Only for Java programs','Only for programs with < 100 lines','["B"]'::jsonb,'hard',45,'Determining if a program will loop forever for all cases is mathematically impossible for a general-purpose computer.','pregenerated'),
